Ahem, I didn't think about the need to support more than one drivers.

The original validation logic is:
for all ports (qos/qos_plugin.py line 219)
for all rules (qos/qos_plugin.py line 223)
for any drivers (qos/drivers/manager.py line 141)

Now I changed the raise/pass behavior to returning a boolean.

Theoretically we still run the chance that qosDriverA validates True for portB, while qosDriverB validates False but mechDriverB binds portB. This is possible, right? Is it realistic? I don't know.

Unless each driver cares only about its own ports (that is the ports it bound). For example the ovs driver would validate ports with vif_type==ovs. Other drivers would not even look at ports with vif_type==ovs. But that means we'd need to re-validate qos policies/rules at port binding time - possibly affecting the outcome of port binding. We don't have anything like that today, do we?
